    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1962-10-25T13:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1962-10-25T13:30:00-05:00" n="72"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d72">
                <head>72. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Mission</gloss> to the <gloss
                        type="to">United Nations</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                        State</gloss>
                    <note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d72fn0">Source:<gloss target="#t_USUN1"
                            >USUN</gloss> Files:<gloss target="#t_NYFRC1">NYFRC</gloss> 84-84-001,
                        Outgoing Telegrams. Secret; Eyes Only. Drafted by <persName
                            corresp="#p_SAEII1">Stevenson</persName> and Sisco.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>New York</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1962-10-25T14:30:00-04:00">October 25, 1962, 2:30 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1459. Subject:<gloss target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> on Cuba.</p>
                <p>I saw <persName corresp="#p_UT1">U Thant</persName> this morning and conveyed to
                    him suggestions contained in <gloss target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 1084
                        (<gloss target="#t_USUN1">USUN</gloss> 4963).<note n="1" xml:id="d72fn1">
                        <ref target="#d69">Document 69</ref>.</note> He said he would transmit
                    suggestions to <persName corresp="#p_KNS2">Khrushchev</persName> in form of
                    confidential message.<note n="2" xml:id="d72fn2">For text of <persName
                            corresp="#p_UT1">U Thant</persName>’s letter to <persName
                            corresp="#p_KNS2">Khrushchev</persName>, October 25, see American
                        Foreign Policy, Current Documents, 1962, p. 425.</note> He would also send
                    President <persName corresp="#p_KJF2">Kennedy</persName> note reporting his
                    message to <persName corresp="#p_KNS2">Khrushchev</persName> and asking that US
                    exercise restraint in circumstances.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_UT1">Thant</persName> told me <persName corresp="#p_ZVA1"
                        >Zorin</persName> asked him at 7:30 last night what <persName
                        corresp="#p_UT1">Thant</persName> appeal in Council was going to say.
                        <persName corresp="#p_UT1">Thant</persName> replied that it was based on his
                    appeal to <persName corresp="#p_KNS2">Khrushchev</persName> and
                        <persName>Kennedy</persName>. <persName corresp="#p_ZVA1">Zorin</persName>
                    said he had not received it. After <persName corresp="#p_UT1">Thant</persName>
                    explained to <persName corresp="#p_ZVA1">Zorin</persName> nature of his appeal,
                        <persName corresp="#p_ZVA1">Zorin</persName> replied that it was very bad
                    proposal, since blockade was wholly illegal and that <persName corresp="#p_UT1"
                        >Thant</persName> should be concerned with legality and should not equate
                    lifting quarantine with stopping ships going to Cuba. <persName corresp="#p_UT1"
                        >Thant</persName> replied he was not concerned with legality, but with
                    averting a crisis.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_UT1">Thant</persName> told me that Afro-Asians were
                    putting great pressure on <persName corresp="#p_ZVA1">Zorin</persName> to
                    accept, but that on basis of <persName corresp="#p_ZVA1">Zorin</persName>’s
                    preliminary reaction <persName corresp="#p_UT1">Thant</persName>
                    <pb facs="0232" n="204" xml:id="pg_204"/> expects negative reply. <persName
                        corresp="#p_UT1">Thant</persName> anticipates long legal attack on the
                    quarantine.</p>
                <p>If both sides accept his suspension proposal this afternoon, he thinks <gloss
                        target="#t_SC1">SC</gloss> should recess pending discussion on modalities.
                    Parties should then report what agreement they have reached on modalities and
                    thereafter substantive negotiations could take place without another Council
                    meeting.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SAEII1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Stevenson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
